SCP-5127; 



Item #:  SCP-5127

Object Class:  Safe

Special Containment Procedures:  SCP-5127 is to be kept within a standard secure storage locker at Site-64. Access requires minimum Clearance 2 while being deemed in satisfactory psychological condition by site psychiatric staff. Supervising personnel are not to look through SCP-5127 unless the object is being worn. Personnel accessing SCP-5127 are required to submit to a psychological screening after each session. (See Addendum 5127.2) SCP-5127 is to be kept within a darkened secure storage unit with controlled ventilation at Site-64. Access requires minimum Clearance 3 while being deemed in satisfactory psychological condition by site psychiatric staff. SCP-5127 is not to be exposed to any source of light, natural or otherwise, while outside of a testing environment. Exposing SCP-5127 to light for extended periods is forbidden, as instances of SCP-5127-1 have been shown to pose chemical and reality hazards. Areas exposed to SCP-5127-1 must be immediately ventilated with HEPA or equivalent HVAC filters to prevent Site exposure.

While there is no inherent threat in not doing so, SCP-5127 is to be kept in a darkened containment unit during transport to prevent unintended use. SCP-5127 can be transported unescorted, provided appropriate measures are taken to prevent unauthorized usage or exposure to light.

While SCP-5127 otherwise maintains pristine condition, it is to receive professional polishing once annually to prevent accidental wear on the lenses. SCP-5127 is not to be handled without proper personal protective equipment (PPE). Future requests for polishing are under review.

Temporary Containment Procedure Update:  (See Addendum 5127.1) Per Containment Committee Order 5127.S64.15.1, Dr P█████ is no longer permitted to interact directly with SCP-5127 outside of a testing environment. This order shall persist indefinitely, until such a time a consensus regarding Dr P█████'s mental state has been reached.

Description:  SCP-5127 is a material object resembling circular pink spectacles2). Subjects are usually aware that the cause of this effect stems from SCP-5127, and SCP-5127 can be removed from the wearer at any time. Some subjects have reported that usage of SCP-5127 is comparable to a small dosage of Ecstasy (3,4-Methyl​enedioxy​methamphetamine) differing only in that the effect ends immediately upon removal instead of the standard 3-6 hours. Results vary depending on the mental state and psychological triggers of the subject, but all subjects have reported a general feeling of serenity. SCP-5127's bliss-inducing properties can cause addiction in subjects subjected to long-term use.

SCP-5127-1 is the designation given to 4. Long-term exposure is fatal and will cause death by chemical overdose.

The density, concentration, and composition of SCP-5127-1 are dependent on the type and brightness of light distributed through SCP-5127; with natural light causing little to no production.

Discovery:  Purchased for £7 at ████ Antiques, an antique shop in Windsor, UK, by Foundation personnel. SCP-5127's anomalous attributes were discovered when a researcher from Site-91  before their subsequent purchase. SCP-5127 was later transferred to Site-64 after Site-91 ruled out any possible xenobiological or thaumaturgical origins.

Experiment-5127-01:  Dr A███, in an attempt to test SCP-5127's effective range, propped the object into a position at which it could be viewed through, placed a portrait in front of SCP-5127, and proceeded to move backwards. Dr A███ concluded that SCP-5127's effective range was the human eye's ability to see through it. Stating that: 

Experiment-5127-02:  A camera was placed behind one of SCP-5127's lenses. The footage was reported to have no anomalous properties other than being pink tinted. It seems that SCP-5127 is only effective when used by humans (See Experiment-5127-03; Experiment-5127-05) directly observed by creatures that can see.

Experiment-5127-03:  SCP-5127 was placed on various kinds of animals5 and the status of each specimen was documented. All instances in which the subject could see through SCP-5127 reported activation of their various pleasure centres, with increased serotonin and dopamine production.

Experiment-5127-04:  One (1) D-class diagnosed with chemically-imbalanced depression was instructed to wear SCP-5127 as one usually would. The D-class reported feeling  and proceeded to sing a rendition of Louis Armstrong's What A Wonderful World, despite there being no green trees or flowers of any kind in the vicinity. When the object had been removed from the D-class (only minimal resistance was present) the subject reported that he no longer suffered from depressive episodes, but was able to experience feelings related to sadness again.6

Experiment-5127-05:  One (1) D-class was given a standard tactical flashlight (250 Lumens) and asked to shine light through SCP-5127 and observe the object's effects. Upon shining the beam through SCP-5127's left lens, the beam was amplified by approximately 2.5x in brightness, with a final result of light as bright as 630 Lumens. The lightluminescent vapour produced and emitted from SCP-5127, hereby designated SCP-5127-1, has properties similar to its source of origin. The only new property exhibited by SCP-5127-1 is that its optical manipulation is observable to all sighted parties. If a sufficiently bright light source is used to create SCP-5127-1, the light produced can engulf large areas. It is impossible to burn an individual or item using the object's natural magnification properties due to the moisture concentration of SCP-5127-1; no matter how strong the light source.

Addendum 5127.1:  Dr P█████ received SCP-5127 during its transit period from Site-91 to Site-64, where it had been previously monitored by Dr A███. For the duration of transit, and a significant measure of time while in Site-64's custody, Dr P█████ used SCP-5127 for his personal enjoyment and developed an addiction to SCP-5127's euphoric effects. Due to the lack of briefing on the effects of SCP-5127 other than: , administrative action has not been taken against Dr P█████. The only exception being the restriction of access to SCP-5127, which was submitted at Dr P█████'s request.

The following interview was conducted by Site-64's psychology team after Dr P█████ was taken into custody, and SCP-5127 was placed back in containment.



Interviewer:  Dr Andy Westenfelt, Site-64

Interviewee:  Dr P█████, Site-64
